<p>
    The <em>Editor</em> was the bread and butter of Goo Create and what really set it apart from just grabbing <em>Three.js</em> and coding until your brains explode. It allowed you to set up a 3D scene by importing models with or without animation, add interactivity with the State Machine or Scripting, sprinkle it with Post FX, preview your creation and then publish it to the world with a click of a button.
</p>
<p>
    Changing or adding new features to an already visually busy tool required careful consideration of how users interacted with the different components of the GUI to do their work and all the overall flows, from importing their assets to publishing a web-ready and performant version.
</p>
<p>
    Already learned flows and interaction patterns from other software were also an important thing to consider. I avoided reinventing the wheel but was also very keen on improving things that in older tools were cumbersome and sometimes over-engineered.
</p>

