<p>
    Whenever you work with a medium/large team keeping the results consistent requires plenty of attention to details, but it also demands that you do more than what your job description specifies.
</p>
<p>
    Doing wireframes, pixel-perfect mockups, and then handing them off to developers is the perfect recipe for a lot of post-implementation reviews and complaints. The end product will always end up looking just a little bit off.
</p>
<p>
    Because of this, I believe that designers should strive more and more to work on the implementation itself (in my case, mostly nitpicking the HTML/LESS) and to champion for users, testing the interface and the flows before the release. Dipping your feet in development and quality assurance will only make you a more flexible and versatile professional.
</p>

<h2>Iconography</h2>

<p>
    Creative tools have 2 main things in common, regardless of them being for architecture, desktop publishing, or game creation. The first one is the canvas or work area, and the second is a considerable amount of icons with different meanings and purposes because writing labels for all possible actions in such software is always almost impossible.
</p>
<p>
    I had the chance to design and test dozens upon dozens of them. Some were amazingly successful, others required a bit more imagination, but when the "aha" moment came, they were still easy to remember.
</p>

